In this post, I'll look at a few (hopefully uncommon) <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_smell">code smells</a>, I've encountered in my career as a PHP developer.

The below code snippets are all from a class file taken from production code, but were presumably written by an inexperienced developer.  We have an <code>Export</code> class that is responsible for reading records from a MySQL database and exporting them to various formats (CSV, JSON, XML, etc.).

We start out with a class definition and a few private properties: 

<code>php 
class Export {
 // Data Arrays for Code Loads.
  private $media_attributes;
  private $recordType;
  private $jobNumTypes;
  private $agency_role; 
}
</code>

So far this is all well and good.  The properties mix snake and camel case, but it's not the end of the world.

Within our Export class, we have a protected instance method that returns a MySQL record as an array of associative arrays:

<code>  protected function fetchDataCode($ids) {
    return $this->buildExportArray($ids);
  }
  </code>

This is where the code begins its transformation into spaghetti.  Oddly enough, <code>fetchDataCode</code> is simply an alias for another private instance method:

<code>
private function buildExportArray($ids){
    // Settings for export.
    $build_header = $this->build_header;
    $collapse_arrays = $this->collapse_arrays;
    $flat_data_array = $this->flat_data_array; 
    $includeMetaData = $this->include_meta_data;
    // Array to build each line of the output data to.
    $data = array();
    // ...
    return $data;
  }
</code>

Now sometimes you might need to alias a method like this.  

Suppose that we've an decided to implement an interface and want to provide an "adapter method" to satisfy the interface without renaming methods or modifying any legacy code.  In such a case, sure, an alias would make sense.  

In the above example however, it is the simply bizarre repetition of code.

Moving onward.

Within <code>buildExportArray</code>, we also have a few seemingly innocuous assignments:

<code>$build_header = $this->build_header;
    $collapse_arrays = $this->collapse_arrays;
    $flat_data_array = $this->flat_data_array; 
    $includeMetaData = $this->include_meta_data;

     // Load all foreign key data arrays.
      $media_attributes = $this->media_attributes;
      $recordType = $this->recordType;
      $jobNumTypes = $this->jobNumTypes;
      $agency_role = $this->agency_role;
</code>

But generally speaking, in an instance method, there is never a good reason for these kinds of superfluous local assignments.  The above code copies properties from object scope into the local scope for no apparent reason.

One might assume the developer didn't understand the fundamentals of variable scope in PHP; perhaps he wasn't sure an instance variable (e.g.<code>$this->media_attributes</code>) could be accessed directly and passed around like any other variable.

When you can access a property directly, you don't need a local assignment. In addition, a class property has an important advantage over a local variable: it persists the data for the object's lifetime, not just for a single method call.

A few of these kinds of statements might seem harmless, but on a real project, it's the misunderstanding of variable scope that is concerning. When a junior developer begins peppering a codebase with hundreds and hundreds of useless assignments, it can quickly become a nightmare.

In this post, I will demonstrate how to use the adapter pattern to rework legacy code safely without introducing undue risk of regressions into your application.  

Suppose we have an awful legacy class we would like to get rid of called BadCustomer.

class BadCustomer {

}

If you live in a Wordpress bubble, you surely would recognize the function _admin_bar_bump_cb and can quickly infer its purpose by the meaningful cb suffix; in the rest of the PHP world however, this kind of thing is pretty much unforgivable spaghetti code.  

I look at my template and immediately wonder: OMG - who wrote this CSS? Where is it coming from?  To resolve it, I needed to google "wp_head screen css", and <a href="https://davidwalsh.name/remove-wordpress-admin-bar-css">find a developer</a> who had the time and inclination to dig through the PHP in order to remove the offending CSS injection.  

This is precisely the kind of flagrant violation of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Separation_of_concerns" rel="noopener" target="_blank">SoC</a> that a good developer should know to avoid. 

Generally, I prefer not to spend my time digging through PHP source code looking for CSS.  That's one of the most basic rules that we all know - CSS belongs in CSS; PHP belongs in PHP files, Powerpoint don't belong in a directory called "Excel Spreadsheets" and so forth.  

Where should I put my CSS.  General rule of thumb: you would put this code in a file with a .css extension. 

But what about the presentation logic that controls the admin toobar.  We need PHP for that - right?

No, not necessarily. You leave that to theme to implement.

To partake of the admin toolbar, the theme developer would need to add the following class to his or her style.css:

.silly_class_html { margin-top: 32px !important; }
	* .silly_class_html .silly_class_body { margin-top: 32px !important; }
	@media screen and ( max-width: 782px ) {
		.silly_class_html { margin-top: 46px !important; }
		* .silly_class_html .silly_class_body { margin-top: 46px !important; }
	}

.silly_style { }

There should at least be a comment within wp_head: "Adds silly styles to theme".

In Drupal, and most object-oriented web applications, every HTML element is an object with its own class definition.

<div>
Hello World
</div>

As generated by Drupal, this simple looking block of text is very complex and very dynamic.

But let us suppose web developer from the 1990s, or someone who knows nothing about programming apart from HTML wished to change this to the the below:

<div class="cool-greeting">
Hello World
</div>  


This person might be tempted to do the following:

1. Find the HTML file that contains this DIV.
2. Edit line that contains this DIV.
3. Save it and put the file back on the server.

It won't be quite that easy. 

The problem with this code is that it does not properly implement what is known as an interface.

Our HTML Element is an object with its own class definition.  Objects can and should and often do enforce a strict interface that prevents duplicating and tampering with HTML in this manner.


So an HTML element is typically the top-most of many abstraction layers.  Conceptually it is like a cake with the the following layers:

Top to Bottom
instance of HTML "icing"

Abstraction layers (descriptions of the "perfect HTML idea") that ultimately will output perfect HTML

Custom Theme Twig Template*
Core Theme Twig Template (If no custom) 

Custom Theme Preprocessing 
Custom Module Preprocessing 

Core Theme Preprocessing of $variables (If no custom)
Core Module Preprocessing of $variables (If no custom)

Drupal Custom Module Loading
Drupal Core Module Loading

Drupal Bootstrap (connects to DB, starts session, registers services from module configuration YML, plugin discovery, dispatches events)




So the layered, highly abstracted version it is more like this:

index.php
// bootstrap
bootstrap();
// send request to controller
dispatch_event($_GET);

Somewhere in Custom Module...

// We might have built a custom controller instance...it can call whatever (form) to 
// return a response

// We might have a custom implementation of a form or a custom block or custom plugin

// In .module, we are often operating on instances of Core objects to generate our HTML:

// module preprocessing
$variables['greetings'] = []; 
foreach($greetings as $greeting){
  // Set properties of Element object instance
  $elem = new Element();
  $elem->setUuid($greeting['uuid']);
  $elem->setType('DIV');
  $elem->setInnerText($greeting['greeting_text']);
  // Populate $variables with Element Objects
  $variables['greetings'] = [$elem]; 
}

And we often query DB for special data that only applies to specific DIV instance ("cool-greeting" and "Hello World").
$rows = EntityManager::getGreetings();
// returns UUID and greeting_text

// e,g. A record with: DL1ajshdksaj2329847234832343209847 Hello World


But meanwhile back in Core:

Class definitions for EntityManager, Element live here. Event dispatcher logic.










* Note: A twig template can also live inside a custom module if the theme registry is altered.

GET Request to api.jamestarleton.com/datetime.php
Pass optional params: { timezone: "America/New_York" format: "Y-m-d H:i:s" }
Return a formatted date string: E.g.: "2000-01-01 12:00:00" "24 Nov 2018 10:46 am EST"

Suppose you're working in a custom Drupal module, abc_module.module, and need to add a special behavior to a form.

You implement hook_form_alter, and then might try this, which fails:

<code>&lt;?php 

$form['#submit'][] = 'abc_module_do_something_special'; </code> 


What you really mean is:

<code><pre>&lt;?php 

/** 
* @file abc_module.module
*/

/**
* Implements hook_form_alter()
*
* @param $form
* @param $form_state
* @param $form_id
*/
function abc_module_form_alter(&$form, FormStateInterface &$form_state, $form_id) { 

  $delete_form_ids = ['node_page_delete_form'];

  // Target a specific form to do something special.
  if (in_array($form_id, $delete_form_ids) ) {

    // What you really mean:
    $form['actions']['submit']['#submit'][] = 'abc_module_do_something_special';
  }

}

function abc_module_do_something_special(&$form, FormStateInterface &$form_state, $form_id) {
  drupal_set_message(t('Something special on form ID ' . $form_id));
}</pre>
</code>
